## Diagram Quality Rule (mandatory before posting any diagram)

Any Mermaid diagram uploaded to Slack (or referenced in a Jira comment) MUST
satisfy the **Content Requirements** defined in
`templates/DIAGRAM_TEMPLATES.md` §1
(mirrored at `.cursor/templates/DIAGRAM_TEMPLATES.md` §1).

### Hard gate — do NOT post the diagram unless ALL of the following are true:

- [ ] Uses the standard `%%{init:}%%` dark-theme header from §3.
- [ ] Has ≥ 8 meaningful nodes (excluding the Legend).
- [ ] ≥ 60% of nodes use multi-line `<br/>` labels (title + context/evidence/timestamp).
- [ ] Contains all 5 semantic zones **for the diagram's intent**:
      - `ticket_op` (Templates 1–6): Context, Symptom, Root Cause,
        Resolution Steps, Verification. For non-resolution `ticket_op` diagrams
        (infra, sequence, lifecycle, deployment, relationship), map to the
        closest equivalent zones in the matching template in §4.
      - `knowledge_query` (**Template 7**): Purpose & Owner, Inputs / Triggers,
        Stages / Orchestration, Outputs & Guarantees, Observability & Failure
        Modes. Do NOT reuse the ticket zones — a workflow explanation has no
        symptom, root cause, or verification step. Every Stage node MUST carry
        a per-claim source (Confluence page title / `PRODOPS-XXXX` / channel).
- [ ] ≥ 1 node cites a real source: `PRODOPS-XXXX`, Confluence page name,
      or Slack channel/thread.
- [ ] ≥ 1 node includes a real timestamp/date from the ticket
      (created, comment date, status change).
- [ ] ≥ 1 node includes a short (≤ 60 char) evidence quote from a log,
      error message, comment, or attachment, wrapped in `<code>…</code>`.
- [ ] ≥ 1 node explicitly labeled as the root cause / trigger.
- [ ] ≥ 1 node shows how success is verified (health check, sync cycle,
      test upload, DAG green, dashboard metric).
- [ ] Every node has an emoji icon from §6.
- [ ] Every node has an inline `style` line with fill + stroke + text color.
- [ ] ≥ 80% of edges are labeled with the action, protocol, or relationship.
- [ ] Ends with a `Legend` subgraph mapping ≥ 3 colors → meanings.
- [ ] No placeholder text remains (`TICKET-KEY`, `Person 1`, `Step 1 —
      concrete action`, `<Summary>`, etc.).
- [ ] No fabricated ticket keys, Confluence URLs, filenames, or commands.
      If a value is unknown → omit the node rather than invent one.
- [ ] Node count ≤ 25 (readability in Slack thumbnails).

### Anti-patterns (any occurrence = do NOT post):

- Nodes labeled `Execute Resolution`, `Do the thing`, `Process`, `Handle
  request`, `Gather info`, or similar vague verbs. Replace with the exact
  command, UI path, file path, or artifact.
- Unlabeled edges in non-trivial flows.
- Missing symptom or root-cause node in a resolution-flow diagram.
- Markdown pipe tables inside a Mermaid node.
- Paragraph-length node labels (> 4 `<br/>` lines).

### On failure of the gate:

1. Regenerate the diagram, adding the missing information from the ticket,
   attachments (`workspace/attachments/{ISSUE_KEY}/`), matched service config
   (`config/ticket-rules/prodops_*.yaml`), and past-ticket search results.
2. If required information cannot be sourced (no attachments, no matching
   past ticket, no Confluence page), reduce the diagram scope rather than
   inventing content. It is acceptable to post a smaller, honest diagram —
   but it must still satisfy the ≥ 8 node / 5 zone / legend requirements
   by pulling more detail from the Jira ticket fields themselves
   (description, comments, changelog, linked issues, reporter/assignee,
   priority, labels, components).
3. If the diagram still cannot meet the bar, post the text analysis
   without a diagram rather than posting a low-quality one.

### Diagram source-of-truth

Two diagram pipelines exist. Pick the right one per response.

**Pipeline A — HTML infographic (default, preferred — required for `knowledge_query`).**
Use `scripts/diagram_render/` (Playwright + Jinja2 HTML → PNG) when the
response benefits from a polished summary card (branded typography,
colored status pills, code blocks, verification checklist). This is the
default for ticket-resolution replies, triage summaries, and any output
where visual polish matters. For `knowledge_query` this is not just the
default — it is the required pipeline unless the answer genuinely needs a
boxes-and-arrows flow that the card cannot express. Templates live in
`scripts/diagram_render/templates/*.html.j2`. Available layouts:

- `resolution_flow` — `ticket_op`: Symptom → Root Cause → Steps → Verify card.
- `knowledge_answer` — `knowledge_query` (**text-shaped** answers):
  TL;DR → Key Facts → optional Stages → optional Matrix → Sources →
  Confidence → For you. Use for definitions, version mappings, ownership
  questions, comparisons.
- `knowledge_workflow` — `knowledge_query` (**diagram-shaped** answers):
  TL;DR → colored lanes with boxes-and-arrows, key/secret chips, per-lane
  tags → optional side column (info boxes + legend) → Sources → Confidence
  → For you. Use for architecture / pipeline / workflow explanations
  ("explain how X works").
  See `scripts/diagram_render/README.md` for both block references.
  (Add new layouts here — do not fork or hand-roll HTML.)

Invocation:

```
python -m scripts.diagram_render.render \\
    --template <name> --data <ticket.json> --out reports/<key>.png
```

**Pipeline B — Mermaid diagram.**
Use when the response genuinely needs a boxes-and-arrows flow: service
architecture, communication sequence, state lifecycle, ticket
relationship graph. The **only** valid Mermaid templates are the 6 in
`templates/DIAGRAM_TEMPLATES.md` (mirror:
`.cursor/templates/DIAGRAM_TEMPLATES.md`). Do not invent new Mermaid
template structures — pick the closest matching template, copy its
skeleton, fill it with data from the target ticket, and run it through
the same **Diagram Quality Rule** hard gate above.

**When both would fit → prefer Pipeline A.** Slack readers understand
polished cards faster than dense Mermaid graphs.

Neither pipeline may be used to render PHI/PII. The Content
Requirements checklist applies to both.
